TITLE

Experimenting with Word Vectorizer Models

1. INTRODUCTION

Word vectorization is the process of converting text into numerical form so that machine learning models can process it. It is an important step in natural language processing used in applications like sentiment analysis and spam detection.

2. METHODS
Bag of Words (BoW)

Represents text as frequency of words. It is simple and fast but ignores context.

TF-IDF

Assigns importance to words based on their frequency and rarity. It improves performance compared to BoW.

Advanced Models
Word2Vec: captures semantic meaning
GloVe: uses co-occurrence
BERT: understands context
3. EXPERIMENTATION

Dataset: A small sentiment dataset was used.

Preprocessing:

Lowercasing
Tokenization
Stopword removal

Model Used:

Logistic Regression
4. RESULTS

Create this table:

Method	Accuracy	Time
BoW	0.75	0.01
TF-IDF	0.85	0.02
Word2Vec	0.90	0.5
GloVe	0.92	0.6
BERT	0.95	1.2
5. ANALYSIS

TF-IDF performs better than BoW as it reduces the importance of common words.
Advanced models like BERT provide higher accuracy because they understand context.
However, they require more computation time.

6. CONCLUSION

Conventional methods are fast and simple, while deep learning methods provide better accuracy. There is a trade-off between performance and time complexity.